Inflation in Europe has slipped on food
Accelerated inflation, measured in the euro area, is mainly due to the rapid rise in food prices.
In November, price increases in the 13 euro area countries were higher than forecast, after an inflation rate of 2.6 percent in October, an annual inflation of 3.1 percent was recorded, the European Community statistics office in Luxembourg said.
Official forecasts indicated only 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the U.S., British and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the key interest rate by saying that falling interest rates, along with rising commodity prices and falling unemployment rates, would lead to an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to keep the inflation rate below but close to two percent.
According to one analyst, it is Catch 22 for the ECB: “we must deter” inflation so that we no longer have to intervene on this subject at a later date.
In Germany, the inflation rate of 3.3 per cent is a record in the last 12 years and in Spain, it has risen from 3.6 to 4.1.
Inflation in the euro area has taken off due to the rapid rise in food and energy prices.
Cereal futures market ratings increased by 88 percent and the price of soybeans also reached its highest value since 1973.
The price of food oil and dairy products also increased significantly in 2007.
This year, the world oil price rose 52 percent, and last month, a barrel of black gold cost nearly $100.
According to the ECB, in 2008 the inflation rate will go from 2.1 this year to 2.5 percent but, in 2009, it will fall to 1.9.
According to analysts, the 12-month inflation rate remains around 3 percent, however, for the next 3 to 4 months, the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to lower the policy rate twice in 2008.
Gallup points to government crisis
After a long stagnation, the number of supporters of Fidesz (Alliance of Young Democrats) increased significantly in early December, so since 2002 it currently has the largest number of supporters, while Gallup (Survey Institute) has never before seen such low socialist support, namely 13 percent.
For loyal voters, the difference would represent, due to the greater determination of the opposition voters, a support of more than two-thirds (71 percent) against the support of one-fifth (20 percent) for the MSZP (Hungarian Socialist Party).
According to the poll, the MDF (Forum of the Hungarian Democrats) and the SZDSZ (Alliance of Free Democrats) are below the threshold of parliamentarians: their support is two percent across the entire population.
On the faithful voters certain to go to vote, the number of supporters of both parties increased by 1 percent.
The economic climate has continued to deteriorate compared to the previous lowest point, the proportion of those who considered that the economic situation in the country was particularly serious has never been higher, it amounts to 41 percent and according to 46 percent supplementary the situation is quite serious.
After the more optimistic outlook of last spring and summer, families are again more pessimistic about their financial situation.
For next year, the majority of the population expects a worsening and only one-tenth expects an improvement.
Last December, 71 percent of respondents, a majority never seen in previous Gallup polls, felt the prime minister was doing his job badly rather than well.
13 percent of respondents have confidence or much confidence in Ferenc Gyurcsány while 38 percent support Viktor Orbán.
54 percent do not trust the prime minister at all and 27 percent the president of Fidesz.
One indicator of the change in the political situation is the proportion of society thinking that dissatisfaction with the Prime Minister can be addressed without a change in government.
While after the October riots, 35 per cent of respondents wanted the government and the prime minister to remain in office, the current rate is only 20 per cent. The relative majority (33 per cent) believes that holding new elections would be the solution to this situation.
When asked about the intention to vote, 60 percent of respondents said they would definitely go to vote and the additional 20 percent said they would probably go to vote.
To make the comparison, for a "legislative election to be held next Sunday", only 55 percent of respondents would certainly participate and 15 percent would probably participate.
74 percent of people would say no to tuition fees in higher education, 79 percent would say no to consultation fees, and 84 percent would say no to hospital fees.
When we look only at the same proportions of people who expressed their intention to vote in the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 percent of voters would reject the introduction of registration fees, consultation fees and hospital stay fees, respectively.
Auchan is the most expensive, Tesco increased its prices by almost twenty percent
The hypermarkets located in the Budaörs business triangle maintained last year’s average price increase of 16 percent, except that this year the VAT rate did not increase.
Article by Napi Gazdaság (Daily Economy)
This year, in the commercial triangle of Budaörs, the usual daily Christmas basket also increased by 16 percent on average, a value increase of well over a thousand forints was displayed in all hypermarkets.
Prices, which “already flew” in grocery stores last December, no longer jumped sharply from the previous high base.
Nevertheless, consumers are obviously shocked to see that items purchased significantly below nine thousand forints last year now cost more than ten thousand forints.
The Daily Basket in the surveyed hypermarkets exceeded the psychological threshold of ten thousand forints by a minimum of 91 forints.
And the highest value of the basket was 10,573 forints.
(In 2003, this value was 6,800 forints.)
Prices for Unicum and live fish remained almost at last year's level, however prices for turkey fillet, nut and poppy have risen sharply.
In stores, the price of flour and bread followed data from the KSH (Central Institute of Statistics) but, at Auchan, bread of one kilo was found at 139 forints only.
Competition did not lower the price of the product below 200 forints.
It was amazing to see, also in this hypermarket, that the price of the two-liter bottle of Coca-Cola was below 200 forints, so it cost only 257 forints per bottle of Coca-Cola.
However, this year, in terms of Daily Basket, Auchan was the most expensive and Cora the cheapest.
According to our calculations, Cora increased the price of its daily Basket by 15 percent while Tesco and Auchan increased them by about 18 percent and 18 percent respectively.
By comparing last year’s most expensive basket and this year’s cheapest basket, we see a gap of 12 percent while the difference between last year’s cheapest and this year’s most expensive one is 21 percent.
Prices increased by 1,480 forints on average.
Last year, prices rose by 1,206 forints on average, while the impact of the VAT rate increase was already noticed in last year's Christmas prices.
As a result of this process, hypermarkets were not able to determine clearly what margin to apply to products because they were unable to predict the impact of price change on consumption.
(If a trader miscalculates the rotation of a product, they risk losing a large profit on the margin adapted to the intensity of the trade.)
Due to the change in the VAT rate, the price increase in the Daily Basket has evolved so excessively that the most expensive basket was 1,720 forints above the value of that of 2006 when the difference between the cheapest baskets was only 844 forints.
This year, the difference was not so excessive as the value of the most expensive basket was 1,630 forints higher than last year and the least expensive prices increased by 1,284 forints as well.
As we approached the two Christmas seasons, we saw a catastrophic increase in prices, in less than 20 months the prices of everyday items increased by more than 30 percent in hypermarkets.
(This does not necessarily confirm KSH data: for some basic supplies, the statistics institute has seen price increases of more than 30 percent in 12 months.
This is the case for example of flour and egg.)
According to the daily basket of the latter, this seems almost absurd since the price level of this product, already very expensive last year, has increased by just over 10 percent compared to the base.
According to the indices, the flour suppliers occupy a stronger position than the egg suppliers because they have managed to accept the sudden increase in prices also by the multinationals.
In the commercial gold triangle, hypermarkets do not complain, they constantly record good years.
In our experience, the majority of customers no longer look at prices in the three hypermarkets visited.
They buy everything in quantity, they take the long-preserving food by pallets.
On Wednesday morning, large queues formed at the cash registers of the three hypermarkets as the number of customers increased sharply.
However, according to our information, the turnover is lower in the province, many multinationals complain to survey companies that they do not even reach the expected turnover, not only for food but also for sustainable consumer items.
Many hospitals save money on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections, mainly caused by the incorrect use of antibiotics, were registered in hospitals.
The hygienic conditions of hospitals, the insufficient number of beds, the overwork of medical personnel do not help to block infections, says the chief physician of the National Center for Epidemiology.
Many hospitals also save on disinfectants
Not long ago, an MRSA infection was diagnosed in the trauma department of János Hospital.
The antibiotic-resistant bacteria was detected on a man hospitalized following a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year a similar infection occurred in the same place.
The injured in a serious car accident came out of the hospital but shortly after he had to return due to an MRSA infection and, since then, doctors have not been able to do him a major operation because of the bacteria that is in his body.
As of 10 December this year, 1,094 hospital infections generated by a multidrug-resistant pathogen have been reported to the National Nosocomial Surveillance System, said Karolina Böröcz, chief medical officer of the National Center for Epidemiology.
Namely, this is the number of infections caused by a multidrug-resistant pathogen that has actually been registered in hospitals and for the rest we have no information.
About two-thirds of infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSA, i.e. methicillin-oxacillin-resistant staphylococcus aureus.
A third of people carry Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their noses without it developing a disease.
Infections caused by SA (such as angina, tonsillitis, skin infections, traumatic infections) respond well to antibiotics, they are easily curable.
However, if antibiotics are used excessively or inappropriately, the bacteria, which reacts well to antibiotics, will develop a bacteria that is well resistant to antibiotics that will quickly proliferate in poor hospital conditions.
In case of temporary or prolonged malfunction of the immune system, this bacterium can cause serious hospital infections, such as a traumatic infection or sepsis, on elderly patients, of small weights or with a weakened organism.
According to the managing doctor of the János hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infections, these infections are part of the daily life of hospitals.
We must not confuse the infection with the epidemic, we do not find MRSA only the one or we are not looking for them, said Tibor Nyulasi.
SAs are resistant to antibiotics.
“These patients are isolated, caregivers wear rubber gloves and protective masks and we have antibiotics to treat them,” said Tibor Nyulasi.
Hospitalized patients are first checked for MRSA, but infection cannot always be prevented.
Sample collection is not fashionable
The vast majority of MRSA infections could be prevented, but the current conditions and circumstances in Hungarian hospitals are not favorable for preventing the development and proliferation of multidrug-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
As this infection occurs mainly in hospitals and seniors' homes, hospitals should monitor hospitalized patients and isolate patients with MRSA immediately.
However, microbiological sampling is not in fashion in Hungarian hospitals.
It should be noted that the National Social Security Fund does not fund these examinations.
Most cases only emerge if the MRSA infection is detectable on the patient, said the chief physician of the epidemiological center.
The European Union has strict recommendations on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also Hungarian guidelines for the cure of certain infections and syndromes.
Efforts must be made to target antibiotic therapy, i.e. microbiological examinations should be carried out to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always take this into account.
Microbiological sampling is even rarer in outpatient care and basic care, said Karolina Böröcz.
Many hospitals save money on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSAs proliferate from one patient to another most often through medical personnel.
It is therefore essential to wash your hands, put on gloves and protective masks, but there are also significant gaps in hospitals in this area.
MRSA proliferates by infection transmitted by inhalation of droplets and by contact. However, due to conditions in Hungarian hospitals, the contaminated patient cannot always be isolated.
In addition, the rooms are often full, the beds are often too close to each other, while in terms of the epidemic, the patients should be at least 1.5 meters away from each other.
Unfortunately, we also find that hospitals, in a difficult financial situation, save on disinfectants, they lack nurses, there are many patients, so the risk of contamination is even greater, said Karolina Böröcz.
According to Karolina Böröcz, in hospitals where preventive measures are followed, the number of infections is demonstrably lower or the proliferation of the pathogen can be blocked.
Government project against MRSA
Treatment of MRSA infection is an exorbitant expense for social security funds, which is why this infection is being combated everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has established a program to prevent or reduce the incidence of MRSA.
According to published data, this program is effective and MRSA infections show a decreasing trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) highlights the prevention of the incidence of multidrug-resistant pathogens (such as MRSAs) as well as the prevention of hospital infections caused by these pathogens as a priority.
The Commissioner, the author of a fatal accident, was not in a state of drunkenness
The official statement regarding the fatal accident caused by the Commissioner of the 22nd arrondissement was prepared.
It can be ruled out that the commissioner of the 22nd arrondissement, who has since resigned from his post, who crushed a pedestrian causing his death last Tuesday, would have driven in a state of drunkenness or dizziness, said Attila Morvai, a spokesman for the capital's Public Prosecutor's Office after the relative finding was established.
The finding confirmed the first result of the investigation that already found that the former commissioner had not consumed alcohol before getting behind the wheel
Last Tuesday, the former head of the police station of the 22nd arrondissement crushed a 55-year-old man who found himself in front of him when he turned, with his personal car, in Kossuth Lajos street of the 22nd arrondissement. The man wanted to cross the road by not going through the pedestrian crossing.
(Furthermore, the fact that he crossed the road outside the pedestrian crossing is not an mitigating circumstance, according to the Highway Code a car that initiates a turn must let pedestrians pass.)
The pedestrian died after being transported to the hospital.
As a result of this accident, the Commissioner resigned from his position and requested his retirement because, according to the police communication, this accident greatly upset him.
The investigation into this case is being conducted by the Budapest Public Prosecutor's Office.
Attila Morvai also mentioned that the former commissioner cooperated early on with the magistrates charged with conducting the investigation.
Additional €400 million for infrastructure
János Veres, Hungarian Finance Minister, and Marta Gajecka, Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB), signed on Friday in Budapest three agreements worth a total of €400 million on a credit line to support education, transport and environmental infrastructure as well as energy.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) adopted a budget of €300 million for the Hungarian budgetary financing of transport and environmental projects to be carried out from the Cohesion Fund, of which a credit agreement worth €100 million has already been signed by the parties.
The agreement on the EUR 150 million appropriation also concerns the budgetary financing of education-related projects.
The EIB has approved a total of €300 million for Hungary, with the remaining €150 million to be used later, following the extension of the credit agreement.
The parties have signed a contract of 50 million euros for innovation, the state budget will use this envelope in the first place as part of the research and development project to be carried out at the University of Debrecen.
During the negotiations, the project of metro line 4 was also discussed.
The parties agreed that they would re-discuss the possible modification of the initial contract when Hungary finalised the details of the financing of the metro with the EU.
According to János Veres, this could happen in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has provided a total of EUR 8.4 billion to finance 113 projects in Hungary.
The EIB grants its loans at the interest rate linked to EURIBOR, with a grace period of 8 years and no commitment fee.
Bulgaria, paradise of the EU real estate market
The evolution of the Bulgarian real estate market is spectacular, the attention of all Europe is turned towards this Balkan country little mentioned in the past.
What, or and who bought on this EU market which is always the cheapest but which will quickly become expensive?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
Currently, in real estate, Bulgaria is undoubtedly the most popular target in Eastern Europe with its ski apartments and cheap seaside houses.
In the mountains, the most popular areas are Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa and, by the sea, Albena, the "Golden Sands", the "Sunshine Coast", the old Sozopol and Nessebar but they are increasingly looking for a building in the Kavarna and Balcik area as well.
According to the analysts of Re/Max Bulgaria, sooner or later the central region of the country, namely Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna, will also arouse the interest of investors and they are also increasingly buying in the very inexpensive corner of Ruse.
Sofia, the capital, offers attractive opportunities as well, with commercial and office surfaces promising the highest depreciation rate.
Bulgaria is on track to become one of the most attractive golf paradises in Europe and thus be a priority destination, after the summer and winter seasons, also in the other two seasons of the year.
More vigilant investors are already buying in large numbers, for example in the corner of Bansko.
According to analysts, people who buy a building in Bulgaria are at the same time looking to change their life, their lifestyle.
Most of the buyers are English but others are coming from France, Belgium, Spain and more and more from Romania.
Maltese and Cypriot investors are also present. On the Black Sea shore and in the most renowned ski resorts, we traditionally meet many Russian buyers.
Foreign buyers are divided into three groups, says Georgij Jankov, Regional Director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
People who plan to settle in buy renovated buildings, at a price ranging from 50 to 100 thousand euros, or old dilapidated houses, at a price ranging from 5 to 15 thousand euros, which are then renovated.
The criteria are easy access and communication possibilities, proximity to a large city, shops and in general that of the local doctor.
The second group includes buyers of second homes (since last December, Bulgaria is listed among the top 10 holiday destinations in Germany).
The third group is made up of commercial investors who buy in the hope of achieving medium- to long-term capital gains.
The price of buildings in the capital continues to rise as demand grows.
In the European Union, real estate prices are the lowest in Bulgaria. However, in the last 5 years, they have increased by 21 percent each year.
The increase in real estate prices essentially exceeds the increase in wages.
Fodor and the six percent Hungarians
According to the communication of Gábor Fodor, Minister of Environment and Water, the meetings of the professionals end on Tuesday, however, Wednesday, after the official opening, the negotiations of the ministers on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world will discuss the Bali Roadmap to define the efforts to be made after the emissions reduction period defined by the Kyoto Protocol until 2012.
At the moment, there are lively discussions on this issue between developing and developed countries.
The United States also reported that, at the moment, it does not want to discuss exact figures, while it was ready to sign an agreement on reducing greenhouse gas emissions by 25 to 40 percent from 1990 levels by 2020.
Another important topic of the conference is whether developed countries are committed, excluding emission reductions, to providing financial and technological assistance to countries in need.
An agreement has also been signed on aid to developing countries.
The aid fund defined by the Kyoto Protocol will be managed by a 16-member board of directors likely under the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF), Piac és Profit (Market and Profit) said.
Six percent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, Gábor Fodor, Minister of Environment and Water, confirms the EU’s ambition to retain its role as a flagship in global efforts to protect the climate and to encourage the signing of the new international agreement by 2009.
The minister explained that the EU is committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 percent by 2020 from 1990 levels, regardless of the success of the signing of the “Post-2012 Agreement”, and was ready to reduce them by up to 30 percent if other major regions of the world and/or developing countries were also prepared to make commitments tailored to their responsibilities and capabilities.
Gábor Fodor recalled that in 1997, the signatory countries of the Kyoto Protocol had aimed at a total reduction of 5.2 per cent and all 15 EU members of that time took the commitment on 8 per cent less.
Hungary has made a commitment to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6% compared to the level of the period between 1985 and 1987, our country will fulfill its commitment, recalls the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
The stakes are high in Bali because the long-term international agreement on climate policy must be put in place within two years, otherwise the entry into force of the agreement would certainly be postponed after 2012. In this case, the commitments of reduction below the values provided for in the Kyoto Protocol would not be immediately followed by a new international system of emission reductions, the need for which has been emphasized in the new IPCC report.
The reduction in emissions would be delayed and the increase in the average temperature of the Earth by more than 2 degrees celcius could no longer be avoided which, according to scientists, would have extremely serious and irrevocable consequences.
British Army recruits on YouTube
British Army units are posting footage from its operations in Iraq and Afghanistan on the video-sharing site with the aim of becoming popular.
First, it was the British Air Force (RAF) that became passionate about YouTube: special units operating in Afghanistan upload video footage of operations against the Taliban since March 2006, the BBC said.
These recordings, taken using miniature cameras mounted on the helmet, are checked at the air force operations headquarters in Kandahar and then transferred to London where compatriots upload them to the Internet.
The political message is unavoidable
Air Force soldiers have already passed 139 footage on the net this way and their "chain" has been watched by more than 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defence registered as the "defenceheadquarters" in the spring of 2007 and is releasing videos about operations in Iraq and Afghanistan while the Commonwealth Office and the international peacekeeping forces in Iraq (MNFI) also have their own channels on YouTube.
Mission in Afghanistan
According to the Ministry of Defence, the videos were also used to make the general public aware of the real objectives of the army's presence abroad.
The propaganda published in this way costs practically nothing compared to the usual recruitment advertisements passed on television, Gordon Mackenzie, a defense consultant, communicated to the BBC. On the other hand, it also inevitably carries a political message since it justifies in a special form the merits of the military operations decided by the government.
The Americans made a game.
The army is annoyed because, apart from the carefully composed and censored videos, amateur videos have passed on the sharing site that also present, for example, the deaths of soldiers: in the “official”, somewhat hypocritical propaganda films, the officers do not avoid talking about the losses but they never present the bloody side of the fight.
Moreover, many videos had already gone online showing the areas of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan that were being carried out in real mission, but the British army has only recently rushed to upload these videos.
Americans recruit a bit differently using the free-to-download America's Army shooting game, where the player can put himself directly in the shoes of the soldiers in a more or less real simulation.
Christmas raffle and donuts in ministries
Mónika Lamperth, the Labour Minister, does not seem to be sentimental: instead of celebrating Christmas, she will hold a year-end meeting with her collaborators who will be able to say goodbye to the year 2007 with donuts and coffee.
Another ministry will host a party with live music, another will enchant officials with a tombola and offer a drink to create a Christmas atmosphere.
Party, Christmas atmosphere, concerts and buffet, so the power is fun.
Public authorities are also preparing for Christmas.
This year’s biggest Christmas party will be hosted by the Ministry of Defence, but it will not be invited by the Ministry’s employees.
At Christmas, Orphans, the children of the fallen soldiers will receive gifts, for missionary Christmas, the family members of the soldiers currently serving in foreign missions are invited and a press reception will also be held.
