During this holiday, the Christmas atmosphere will be rigorous, there will be actors and also a raffle.
The NFÜ Christmas has cost 4,700,000 forints and was organized Wednesday in the building of the National Council of Justice (ILO) with concerts and dinner.
The rental of the room costs one million forints, the rest was spent on the more than four hundred guests.
According to our information, an NFÜ service is invited to another Christmas party that is organized with European money by the National Economic Development Centre, the tendering company.
The building of the Théâtre de la Gaîté was rented for these purposes.
This information has not been confirmed by MAG Zrt because we have not been able to reach the person in charge.
Costume is not mandatory
The ILO building was not only home to the NFÜ but also to the Ministry of Justice and Police, which, instead of a Christmas party, held a ball on the occasion of Saint Luca on 7 December.
The ILO did not charge them for the use of its rooms.
The ball had five hundred people.
The party began with the minister's welcome and dinner was followed by a dance party on live music.
Answer to the question of [origo]: Evening dress was not at all obligatory at this ball.
Ministries of health, labour and local communities are preparing a sober party.
The Ministry of Health will hold a show and party for its employees, within its walls, for 400,000 Forints.
On the other hand, Mónika Lamperth, Minister of Labour, does not officially invite her collaborators to a Christmas party but to a working meeting at the end of the year.
One hundred and eighty people are expected to be invited to have a coffee and eat doughnuts, the press service said, the party will cost as much as 350,000 forints.
Gordon Bajnai, Minister of Local Government, will simply invite his employees to have a drink in the classroom of the Ministry of Local Government and Territorial Planning.
The Ministry of Finance (PM) will host a Christmas party in its large hall at which 436 employees are expected.
He plans to spend 2,500 forints per guest including a buffet and a drink.
Since the arrival of János Veres, the employees of the PM celebrate Christmas every year in the same way.
There is no planned party atmosphere, the official character is reinforced not only by the minister's presentation but also by the time of the party taking place in the afternoon.
The Ministry of Agriculture will host a reception on January 20 to celebrate the new year, the Christmas party will not take place.
The reception will be held at Vajdahunyad Castle, located in the City Wood, and according to the ministry's communication, 1,000 forints per person are calculated for the hundred guests.
According to the press service, this will be a very simple cocktail to which only foreign diplomats accredited in Hungary will be invited.
These cocktails, organized annually, are started with a few words of welcome from the minister followed by a modest meal.
The Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Ministry of Education and Culture do not celebrate Christmas at all, the respective press services have informed [origo].
The Ministry of the Environment's press service did not know the price of the official Christmas party.
However, more than 400 people were invited to the festivity held at the Museum of Decorative Art.
The forces of the mega-strike are gathering
The unions of the League and the National Association of Workers' Councils will set up their strike commission on Friday to coordinate Monday's indefinite strike.
On Saturday, a general protest assembly will be held and on Monday, the day of the final vote on the health fund law, the strike will begin.
This action will certainly cause significant traffic jams as rail traffic will be stopped almost completely and the employees of BKV (public transport company) will also strike until 1 p.m.
The unions of the league will announce, Friday afternoon, the details of their strike on Monday, organized with the National Association of Workers' Councils.
The strike commission of LIGA - MOSZ will also be constituted, it will serve as coordinator of Monday's actions.
On Saturday, a protest general assembly will be held and, starting Monday, organizations joining the strike will stop working indefinitely if they fail to reach an agreement with the government.
This means that the date of the end of the strike, starting from the day of the vote in parliament on the health fund law, is not defined.
If the National Assembly does not adopt the Health Funds Act, the unions will immediately withdraw the call for strikes.
On the other hand, if the law is passed, the strike committees will meet and decide on what to do next.
According to Monday's agenda of the National Assembly, it is likely that the vote on the Health Funds Act will only take place late in the evening, or even at night.
Due to the strike scheduled for Monday, major traffic jams are planned: railways will stop work for an indefinite period of time and during the morning part of public transport in Budapest and more than half of Volán companies are at risk of being arrested.
At the same time, at different points in the country, half of the track will also be blocked.
Many trade unions and civil organizations have joined the call for strikes, the list of which is constantly updated on the League's website.
Some organizations report going on strike indefinitely, others have declared a temporary work stoppage.
Until Thursday afternoon the MÁV (Hungarian Railways) and the Free Railway Union (VDSZSZ) failed to reach an agreement on minimum services, but as Christmas approaches, more and more people are taking the train.
According to current communications, public transport in Budapest will go on strike from the start of service until 1 p.m., the Budapest airport between 7 a.m. and 9 a.m., the Industrial Unions of Electricity and Thermal Energy of the League will go on strike for four hours, the Union of Teachers and the Democratic Union of Teachers called for strikes respectively for 2 hours and from 2 hours to 8 hours.
The National Association of Physicians will strike across the country in alternation, the Health and Social Employees Union (EDDSZ) attached to the SZEF will make a two-hour warning strike.
The most important of the four demands, made by the League, requires that the government withdraw its proposal for health reform and submit a new conception to the social debate.
The second claim requires that the new method of calculating the pension to be implemented from next year be introduced in several stages.
The third demand is for a guarantee of retirement before the legal age, which would allow the system to pass the functions it deserves before 2010.
The fourth reason for the action is the rejection by the Free Union of Railway Workers (VDSZSZ), attached to the Unions of the League, of the proposal of the Ministry of Economy and Transport concerning the secondary railway lines and the waiting for another proposal.
Political Capital: The Hungarian Guard increased the country's risk
According to the Risk Analysis Division of Political Capital, the activity of the Hungarian Guard, formed last August, with the support of Jobbik Magyarországért Mozgalom (Movement for a Better Hungary), increases the political risk of Hungary and the region in several ways.
In its “risk warning”, the company notes that, in relation to the activity of the Hungarian Guard, the greatest political risk is already that “in the short term aggressive ethnic clashes can occur following the aggravation of the ethnic tension already existing between the gypsy and non-gypsy population of Hungary”.
The research institute added that the Hungarian Guard's political strategy likely to provoke this situation is the main reason.
As they say, this is explained by one of the main shortcomings of the Hungarian political actors: “public actors have passed the public debate on the Roma affair to representatives of radical and extreme political groups that have based a political strategy on the dispute between Gypsies and Hungarians”.
The problem is aggravated, normal dialogue becomes impossible, extremists are strengthened and the arrival of aggressive conflicts is more likely, they say.
However, according to the research institute, due to the increased attention of the Hungarian and international media, the activity of the Hungarian Guard “significantly deteriorated the image of Hungary abroad, especially regarding the confidence in the stability and democratic maturity of the country”.
They recall that, following the increased publicity given to the reorganization of Hungarian radical and extreme right-wing groups since the fall of 2006, many associations have been formed in Hungary since the summer of 2007, giving themselves the name of "national association of self-defense".
“The common feature of these rallies is that they define themselves as a civilian organization while publicly declaring the preparation of their adherents for defense missions (disasters, national defense, defense of order), armed if necessary, moreover, referring to the inadequacy of the police, the army, in other words the state,” they added.
They pointed out that everything was going according to the method that, based on the rancor of the political society and the parties, seeks to disguise different political ambitions in a civil aspect.
The emphasis on civility and association status is therefore only intended to avoid the legal pitfalls of registering these associations in court, but it is also a political strategy.
The analysis indicates that the activity of the Hungarian Guard is a factor that also increases the risk in relation to neighbourhood relations.
“In recent months, many neighbouring countries have cited the Hungarian Guard as a potential source of risk, and ultranationalist political actors in some neighbouring countries want to justify their anti-Hungarian policy by referring to the Hungarian Guard constitution.
This influences the political stability of the region,” they added.
According to the research institute, the constitution of the Hungarian Guard is not a unique phenomenon in Central Eastern Europe, political risks have increased across the region.
