The party is not marked in red everywhere
In Hungary, the law defines exactly the holidays and, around the holidays, it has become common to reorganize the working days whose number will decrease next year.
The holidays are not uniform in the EU and the US either.
Hungarian legislation distinguishes national and state holidays as well as rest days.
The days of rest are often linked to religious festivals or important historical events.
In Hungary, we celebrate the new year, the last day of the year that ends and the first day of the new year are also days of rest, the latter all the more so that the wake-up callers can rest quietly.
In one year, we have eleven festivals marked in red.
March 15 is a national holiday, commemorating the revolution of 1848, as well as October 23, which is the commemorative day of the revolution of 1956.
On August 20th we celebrate the constitution of our state, May 1st is Labor Day and on November 1st and 2nd we remember our deceased family members and friends.
In addition, we have two days at Easter, at Pentecost and at Christmas.
The days of our state, national or religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, depending on the calendar, it has become common to reorganize the working days in cases where there is only one working day left before or after the holiday marked in red.
It is true that we pay the price of extended weekends by working or going to school the Saturday before the extended weekend.
For many years, the Minister of Labour has ruled in a special regulation on the days of replacement of the days before or after the holidays.
The law extends to all employers and their employees, to public servants and to persons working in the public service.
It does not apply, however, to service societies, institutions that operate continuously and in service, by their vocation, and also for days of rest.
This year, the working days will be changed only around the end of the year: from December 24, life stops almost all over the country because according to experience, the majority of people do overtime or take holidays that they have saved for these purposes in order to be able to spend the days between Christmas and New Year's Day at home.
Next year many holidays fall in the middle or at the end of the week, therefore there will be fewer changes in the level of working days compared to this year.
The calendar will be reorganized for the first time around Labor Day to allow employees to stay at home for four days in a row.
Saturday 25 April will be a working day to have a rest day on Friday 2 May.
Another change is planned for October 23rd: Saturday, October 18th will be a working day replacing Friday, October 24.
On the other hand, next year, the end of the year is under the sign of the holidays because from December 24, everyone will take a non-stop break even if New Year’s Day falls on a Wednesday.
