The Federal Reserve Bank of the United States, the European Central Bank and the British, Swiss and Canadian central banks have decided to fight the financial market crisis together.
More than one hundred billion dollars will be placed in the money markets through auctions.
It will be for banks to sell, through an auction system, the interest rates at which they are willing to borrow money.
For example, the US Fed will auction $40 billion and, in addition, it will provide $24 billion to the European and Swiss central banks.
This is the first time since the September 11 attacks that the central banks of individual states have decided to take such concerted action to prevent or even mitigate the effects of the financial crisis.
"This approach tends to solve the major problems of the economy, namely the growing lack of free capital that banks could lend," Bernard Baumohl of the consultancy Economic Outlook Group wrote in his report to clients.
“Central bank concerted action has reduced the likelihood of a recession in the United States from 65 percent to about 50 percent,” Baumohl said in his report.
Banks have already lost $60 billion from unpaid loans, especially in the United States.
Analysts are still expecting losses in billions.
“If the central banks have chosen this approach, it is that they have to really understand what can still happen,” says ABN Chief Economist Amro Kieran Davies.
“It looks like the situation is really bad,” he adds.
Central banks fear that if banks themselves have difficult access to loans, they will lend more to their customers.
This would reduce consumption and plunge the U.S. economy into a recession that could affect global economic growth.
The central banks made this choice after they failed to bring down London’s interbank rate, called LIBOR, used to borrow on the interbank market.
This meant that banks still feared mutual borrowing, even though the U.S., Canadian and British central banks had repeatedly lowered their interest rates during the fall.
"This will have the same effect as a further fall in interest rates," Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting told Reuters.
