Congress approves the transposition of the Mifid, which came into force on November 1
Alongside its parliamentary formality, which ended today with the Congressional vote on the amendments incorporated into the bill in the Senate, the Government has submitted to a public hearing the regulation that will develop the new law, with the objective of its entry into force before the end of the year.
Representatives of the different groups agreed to highlight the efforts made by Members of Parliament and senators to negotiate and agree on the best regulation to ensure investor protection and to regulate in detail the activities of the agencies for the efficient functioning of the markets.
The Mifid, which amends the Securities Market Act, involves the modernization of financial markets, at a time when it strengthens investor protection, improves the powers of the leaders of the National Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and promotes cooperation between the different leaders of the European Union.
The new regulations will provide financial advisory services to both specialized corporate and legal entities and create a new type of financial services (ESIS), financial advisory companies (FIAs), which merge with securities companies, securities agencies and portfolio management companies.
In addition, it increases the number of systems for the execution of transactions in financial instruments, so that it is possible to add multilateral trading systems and order internationalization systems to regulated secondary markets, which compete with current stock exchange managers.
The Act also requires investment services firms to disclose information on key aspects of their business profile, risk exposure and risk management forms on the market and to keep a record of all transactions they conduct, to facilitate control by the CNMV.
Through the Congressional Economic Commission, several changes have been added, including one that highlights that securitised debts will be considered a “complex” financial instrument given its high risk to the investor, which has proven itself with what happened with the debt of high-risk U.S. mortgages (subprime).
In addition, they took advantage of the management's transposition to legally delimit the functions that graduates in Economics may have 30 years after, in 1977, was approved, the Royal Decree delimiting the professional functions reserved for economists.
For its part, the Senate has incorporated the creation of new figures in the financial sector, such as the mediator, who will work on behalf of a company that will not require the authorization of the CNMV and who will be able to provide its services of marketing products and attracting new clients to different investment firms at the same time.
