The climate of Venus could reveal the future of the Earth.
Scientists said yesterday that Venus has certainly been a pleasant planet to live on.
Data from the European spacecraft in orbit has shown that the planet is certainly twice as small as Earth, contrary to what was previously thought.
Venus is the closest planet to Earth.
These two worlds are virtually the same size, with similar orbits, although Venus is closer to the Sun.
Scientists now believe that billions of years ago, Venus may have had Earth-like conditions, and may even have been habitable.
But the greenhouse effect due to carbon dioxide, atmospheric erosion due to solar radiation coupled with a slower rotation has led Venus to a whole other kind of evolution.
Today the planet is deprived of water, is ravaged by hurricanes and lightning storms and has a surface temperature hot enough to melt lead there.
The findings of Venus Express, the European Space Agency's probe, which has studied the planet for a year, offer a sad vision of the Earth's potential future due to catastrophic climate changes.
Professor Fred Taylor of the Department of Physics at the University of Oxford, one of the leaders of the Venus Express mission, said: “We are beginning to understand why the climate of Venus is so different from that of Earth, although the planets themselves are practically similar.
