Venus is the infernal twin of the Earth.
Despite its hostile atmosphere to life, Venus looks more like Earth than previously thought: the European space probe "Venus Express" has discovered flashes in the atmosphere and wind swirls at the poles, similar to those that appear in winter on Earth.
For nearly three decades, scientists have assumed that there are flashes of lightning on Venus.
The European probe "Venus Express" has brought proof of this today - it has detected electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere: lightning on Venus bursts at a height of about 56 kilometers of cloud, reports Christopher Russel of the University of California in Los Angeles in the scientific magazine "Nature".
According to the famous theory of cyprin, lightning would have made life appear on Earth: the storm would have stimulated reactions in the oceans that led to the formation of amino acids, the cornerstone of life.
"If life has been there, it must have been at a very ancient date in history," says Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
There should be few living things on the surface of Venus today: the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, there are sometimes temperatures of 500 degrees.
“Venus may be Earth’s infernal twin, but it remains a twin,” Russell said.
Why Venus, which looks so much like Earth in mass and dimensions, has been hit by such a different evolution, is the fundamental question of the ASE mission.
The departure of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was an important step in the search for Venus, as no probes were on their way to explore this planet since the 1980s.
In the opinion of the researchers, the most recent research results that have now been presented in several articles of "Nature" do not only underline the uniqueness of Venus within the solar system.
They also show that the commonalities with the Earth of our neighboring planet are more than assumed at first.
Thus the researchers found, in addition to the wind swirls already known at the north pole, a swirl of clouds at the south pole, which rotates even faster.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of air currents in the terrestrial hemispheres in winter, writes a team of researchers around Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second planet in the solar system has almost the same mass as Earth and is, with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers, almost as large.
The planet called the evening or morning star revolves around the sun in just 225 days.
However, it rotates much slower on itself: one Venusian day lasts 243 Earth days.
Although Venus, with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, hardly resembles Earth, scientists assume that the two planets formed under similar conditions.
Of the two, water accumulated and remained on Earth in the form of oceans, but was lost in space on Venus.
And while carbon dioxide has settled on Earth in the form of carbonate, it makes up most of the atmosphere on Venus.
